            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Wikipedia presents Euler's identity as the equation e^{iπ} + 1 = 0, where e is the base of natural logarithms, i is the imaginary unit (i^2 = −1), and π is the circle constant. It points out that this identity is the special case x = π of Euler's formula e^{ix} = cos x + i sin x; plugging in x = π gives e^{iπ} = cos π + i sin π = −1, hence e^{iπ} + 1 = 0.  \n\nWikipedia also emphasizes the identity's aesthetic significance: it links five fundamental constants (0, 1, π, e, i) and several basic operations (addition, multiplication, exponentiation), and is widely cited as an exemplar of mathematical beauty.",
